\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Radio Frequency Identification (RFID) is an identification technology that
 wirelessly transmits the identity of a tag that is attached to an object
 or a person.
 Recently the number of applications that use RFID technology has increased,
 and the reading speed became one of the most critical issues in these applicati
ons.
 In RFID systems, the tags typically share a common communication channel.
 Thus, there is a certain probability of tags collisions, i.e.
 multiple tags answer simultaneously.
 This collision probability naturally increases in dense networks.
 According to EPCglobal class 1 gen 2 standards 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "standard"

\end_inset

, the reader is responsible of coordinating the network and has to avoid
 tags collisions using specific anti-collision algorithms.
 The conventional anti-collision algorithm is the Framed Slotted ALOHA (FSA)
 algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aloha1"

\end_inset

, which is only a Medium Access Control (MAC) layer protocol.
 In this algorithm, only the single tag reply (successful slot) can be decoded
 and identified.
 Therefore, the conventional definition of the expected reading efficiency
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{conv}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the probability of success 
\begin_inset Formula $P(1)$
\end_inset

, which is expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size scriptsize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{_{conv}}=P(1)=\frac{n}{L}\left(1-\frac{1}{L}\right)^{n-1},\label{eq:eff basic equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


