 is the frame length.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main goal is to find the optimal frame length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, which maximizes the reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{conv}$
\end_inset

.
 Based on (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eff basic equ"

\end_inset

), the reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{_{conv}}$
\end_inset

 is maximized to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{_{conv(max)}}=36\%$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $L=n$
\end_inset

 as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aloha1"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some research groups: 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Capture_2011"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013_cap_Letter"

\end_inset

 have concentrated more on the effect of the collision resolving probability
 and the optimum value of the FSA frame length.
 They have proposed another equation for the reading efficiency:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size scriptsize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{_{PHY[3]}}=P(1)+\alpha\cdot P(c),\label{eq:eff_PHY_2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\size default
where 
\begin_inset Formula $P(c)$
\end_inset

 is the probability of collision, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the average collision resolving probability coefficient.
 In this efficiency equation, the RFID reader can convert part of the collided
 slots in to successful.
 Based on this efficiency, the authors have calculated a closed form solution
 for the optimum frame length:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size scriptsize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{_{opt[3]}}=\alpha+(1-\alpha)\cdot n.\label{eq:Lopt_letter_2011}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The authors here have assumed unlimited and equal collision resolving probabilit
ies coefficients.
 For example, the probability to resolve two collided tags is equal to the
 probability to resolve ten collided tags.
 However this is not an accurate assumption, because the collision recovery
 probabilities decrease when the number of collided tags increases, as we
 will see in the next sections.
 Moreover, there is a practical saturation limit for the collision recovery
 capability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another research group 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2012_journal_CR"

\end_inset

 considered the limited RFID readers capability of collision resolving.
 They have proposed a limited reading efficiency expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size scriptsize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{_{PHY[5]}}=\sum_{i=1}^{M}P(i),\label{eq:rff_PHY}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\size default
where 
\size small

\begin_inset Formula $P(i)=\binom{n}{i}\left(\frac{1}{L}\right)^{i}\left(1-\frac{1}{L}\right)^{n-i}$
\end_inset


\size default
, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 represents the number of collided tags that the reader is capable to recover.
 The authors assumed that the probability to recover one tag from 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 collided tags is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $100\%$
\end_inset

 independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, which is not a practical assumption.
 In reality, the probability to recover a single tag from 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 collided tags varies based on the receiver type, the number of collided
 tags 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, and the Signal to Noise Ratio (SNR).
 According to the efficiency equation in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rff_PHY"

\end_inset

), the authors proposed fixed values for the optimum FSA frame length based
 on the collision resolving capability of the RFID reader.
 They calculated these values numerically by searching for the frame length
 which maximize their proposed reading efficiency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper we propose a new reading efficiency metric called Multiple
 Collision Recovery Coefficients Reading Efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{_{MCRC}}$
\end_inset

 which includes a unique collision resolving coefficient for each number
 of collided tags.
 Then, we calculate these coefficients based on a simple RFID reader to
 show how the proposed system could be applied on real-life applications.
 Hence, we propose a novel closed form solution for the optimum FSA frame
 length which maximize the proposed efficiency metric.
 The proposed solution gives a direct relation between the frame length
 and the number of tags 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in the reading area in addition to the collision recovery coefficients.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper is organized as follows: Section II presents the system model
 under multiple collision recovery coefficients in addition to an example
 to calculate the collision recovery coefficients.
 Next, section III presents the proposed closed form for the optimal frame
 length based on the collision recovery coefficients.
 Finally, section IV gives numerical results on the improvements of the
 new optimization criterion, before we conclude in section V.
 
\end_layout

