\begin_layout Standard
According to practical ranges for the collision recovery coefficients, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 ,
\size footnotesize
 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\alpha_{i}\leq1$
\end_inset


\size default
, and 
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}\geq\alpha_{3}\geq\alpha_{4}$
\end_inset


\size default
.
 Therefore, we can proof that the signs of the polynomial coefficients are
 constant and not changing in all ranges of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 and can be as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula $a=+$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b=-$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=-$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d=-$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $e=-$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Descartes’ rules of sign 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Descartes_rule"

\end_inset

, we can count the number of real positive solutions that a polynomial has.
 Assume that the polynomial in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:final_fourth"

\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\beta)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 be the number of variations in the sign of the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a,\, b,\, c,\, d,\, e$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}$
\end_inset

 be the number of real positive solutions.
 According to Descartes’ rules of sign 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Descartes_rule"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\leq\nu$
\end_inset

 which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}=0\, or\,1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\nu-n_{p}$
\end_inset

 must be an even integer.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the above two Descartes’ rules of sign, there is only one valid
 real positive solution for the equation.
 Now, we will identify which solution is the valid one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we have one real solution, so there are two possibilities for the solutions
: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 One positive real solution and the remaining three solutions are negative.
 In this case, all solutions are real and we need just to identify what
 is the root which has the largest values from the four solutions.
 According to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:roots"

\end_inset

), the value of the square roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{Y}$
\end_inset

