 The values of these coefficients are strongly depend on the receiver type.
 For simplicity, calculations of the collision recovery coefficients are
 done based on a very simple RFID reader.
 The reader resolves the collision based on the strongest tag reply.
 Therefore, the collision will be resolved if the strongest tag reply is
 stronger than the summation of the other collided tags at the same slot.
 The main advantage of this reader is that it does not need any channel
 state information (CSI) to recover the strongest tag.
 According to EPCglobal C1G2 standard 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "standard"

\end_inset

, collisions in RFID systems are occurred only at 
\begin_inset Formula $16$
\end_inset

 bits packet called 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

.
 If any single bit error occurred in this packet, the total packed is considered
 lost.
 Therefore, the meaning of the the collision recovery probability coefficients
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that the RFID reader can identify a complete 
\begin_inset Formula $RN16$
\end_inset

 packet from 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 collided tags.
